54 738 Td
(Tireless iteration.) Tj
T*
(110 paper versions. Hundreds of debug plots. No complaints.) Tj
T*
(Basic calculus and algebra.) Tj
T*
(Setting up integrals, changing variables, expanding functions, checking factors.) Tj
T*
(Code generation.) Tj
T*
(Python plots, Fortran interfaces, Mathematica notebooks—all working. No more Python version) Tj
T*
(number conflicts, missing libraries, or syntax errors.) Tj
T*
(Literature synthesis.) Tj
T*
(Combining results from multiple papers coherently and scouring the literature. Make sure to) Tj
T*
(have Claude double check the authors, titles, and journals one by one in the bibliography.) Tj
T*
(What Claude is bad at) Tj
T*
(Maintaining conventions.) Tj
T*
(When conventions are non-standard, it constantly reverts to textbook defaults even if you) Tj
T*
(force it to write the conventions down and stick with them.) Tj
T*
(Honest verification.) Tj
T*
(It says “verified” when it hasn’t actually checked. You have to call it out, insisting, “Did) Tj
T*
(you honestly check everything?” or, “Go line by line and verify every step.” Skills and) Tj
T*
(CLAUDE.md help with this a little, but not enough.) Tj
T*
(Knowing when to stop.) Tj
T*
(It finds one error, thinks it’s satisfied the task, and stops looking. You need to repeat) Tj
T*
(“Check again” until it finds nothing new.) Tj
T*
(Keeping its eye on the prize.) Tj
T*
(It can only handle small steps and loses direction easily.) Tj
T*
(Plot aesthetics.) Tj
T*
(Axis labels, legends, fonts, and colors all need micromanagement to be human-readable.) Tj
T*
(Resisting pressure.) Tj
T*
(If I forced it to think deeply about something, after a while it would just give me the) Tj
T*
(answer I seemed to want, even if it wasn’t justified.) Tj
T*
(The tricks that worked) Tj
T*
(Cross-verification.) Tj
T*
(I had GPT check Claude’s work and vice versa. They caught each other’s errors. For the) Tj
T*
(hardest integral, GPT solved it, and Claude incorporated the solution.) Tj
T*
(Tree structure.) Tj
T*
(Instead of one long document, Claude maintained a hierarchy of task summaries. It works) Tj
T*
(better with things it can look up than things it has to remember.) Tj
T*
(Explicit honesty requirements.) Tj
T*
(In my CLAUDE.md config, I wrote, “NEVER use phrases like ‘this becomes’ or ‘for consistency’) Tj
T*
(to skip steps. Either show the calculation or say ‘I don’t know.’”) Tj
T*
(Repeated queries.) Tj
T*
(Because Claude can stop looking after finding one error, you have to repeatedly ask until it) Tj
T*
(finds no others.) Tj
T*
(One final recommendation I’d give is to move away from the web-based LLMs. These have been) Tj
T*
(around for a while, and are good. But for me the real phase transition was running Claude) Tj
T*
(Code with access to files, terminal commands, agents, skills, memory etc. It makes a big) Tj
T*
(difference.) Tj
T*
(Conclusions) Tj
T*
(This paper started out as an experiment: how close are we to end-to-end science with AI? My) Tj
T*
(conclusion is that current LLMs are at the G2 level. I think they reached the G1 level) Tj
ET
endstream
endobj
