(persist—those things that are essentially human. I can easily imagine theoretical physics) Tj
T*
(becoming like music theory or French literature: an academic discipline appealing to people) Tj
T*
(who just enjoy thinking through a certain lens. It’s a bit ironic that the last 30 years) Tj
T*
(have seen the growth of STEM fields, displacing the humanities, and in the end it may be the) Tj
T*
(humanities are all that survive.) Tj
T*
(In any case, we are not yet in that future. We are in possession of tools that can speed up) Tj
T*
(our workflows by a factor of 10. From my point of view, it’s immensely gratifying to work) Tj
T*
(this way—I never get stuck anymore and I’m constantly learning.) Tj
T*
(Before long, everyone else will catch on. While such efficiency gains will have outsized) Tj
T*
(effects across all domains, one large consequence I foresee in science is that people will) Tj
T*
(work on harder problems: quality, not quantity. That’s what I’m doing. And because of that,) Tj
T*
(I expect to see real advances in theoretical physics, and science more broadly, at a level) Tj
T*
(that is hard to fathom.) Tj
T*
(Epilogue) Tj
T*
(I conducted this project in the last two weeks of December 2025. My paper came out January) Tj
T*
(5, 2026, and made a pretty big splash—I got a flood of emails and invitations to explain it) Tj
T*
(to various physics groups worldwide. It was trending on r/physics for a while and made the) Tj
T*
(water-cooler circuit at a large number of theory departments. When I go to conferences, all) Tj
T*
(anyone wants to talk about is how to use Claude. I visited the Institute for Advanced Study) Tj
T*
(in Princeton in January, and soon after they had an) Tj
T*
(emergency meeting) Tj
T*
(about using LLMs. The word is getting out.) Tj
T*
(Over the past three months or so, physicists have been learning to incorporate LLMs into) Tj
T*
(their research program, for both ideation and technical work. On the ideation side, Mario) Tj
T*
(Krenn has been developing tools to generate ideas, and this has generated some output, such) Tj
T*
(as) Tj
T*
(this paper) Tj
T*
(from early November 2025. Steve Hsu) Tj
T*
(wrote a paper) Tj
T*
(not long after which also used and acknowledged AI in a central way. On the technical side,) Tj
T*
(a) Tj
T*
(paper) Tj
T*
(by my Harvard colleague Andy Strominger and others working with OpenAI included one sharp,) Tj
T*
(challenging technical calculation that \(as I understand it\) a non-public version of GPT did) Tj
T*
(rather autonomously. A) Tj
T*
(follow-up paper) Tj
T*
(and blog includes some of the) Tj
T*
(prompts) Tj
T*
(. I would say that for all these projects, and for mine, physicists are still needed to) Tj
T*
(point the LLMs in the right direction as they have no clue what an interesting problem is) Tj
T*
(yet.) Tj
T*
(I would also contrast these efforts with my own approach:) Tj
T*
(having Claude perform every single step itself) Tj
T*
(. This is a big step forward in showing that there are a set of prompts which can get LLMs) Tj
T*
(to write a long, technical, and rigorous science paper.) Tj
T*
(In addition to the growth in interest, the tools themselves have been steadily improving. I) Tj
T*
(am now doing 100% of my research with LLMs. I don't encapsulate the LaTeX writing anymore) Tj
T*
(since I actually enjoy writing papers and it helps me think, and I still write some) Tj
ET
